</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Monetary Fund has revoked Yugoslavia's membership and laid
down the conditions for its successor republics to become members, writes
George Graham in Washington.
After weeks of deliberations on a legal formula, the IMF concluded that
Yugoslavia had ceased to exist and had therefore ceased to be a member. The
decision lays down the quota of each successor republic, which will also be
the share each must accept of the former Yugoslavia's liabilities to the
Fund, which amount to about Dollars 217m (Pounds 143m).
