<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / IBM to cut 25,000 more jobs: Global capacity to be reduced -
Dollars 6bn charge / Dividend threatened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines, reeling from a global economic slowdown and
a rapidly changing computer market, yesterday announced plans to cut its
worldwide workforce by 25,000, or 8 per cent, next year and sharply reduce
its manufacturing capacity. It will take a Dollars 6bn (Pounds 3.9bn)
fourth-quarter charge to cover the costs.
The news sent the company's shares plunging nearly 11 per cent to close at
Dollars 56 1/8 , down Dollars 6 3/4 . This is their lowest level for a
decade and compares with the 1992 high of Dollars 100 3/8 .
In a sign of the severity of the crisis it faces, IBM made clear that two of
its treasured traditions - maintenance of annual dividend and a policy of no
forced redundancies - were no longer safe.
Wall Street analysts estimated that the company, the world's largest
computer manufacturer, was heading for a 1992 loss after charges of about
Dollars 4.75bn and sentiment towards the company remained extremely
negative.
Mr Stephen Smith of Paine-Webber said: 'These actions don't go far enough
and the outlook for mainframe computers is very bleak.' With the dividend at
risk, he felt that the stock could fall below Dollars 50.
Mr John Akers, IBM chairman, said that while cash flow remained strong,
'current earnings expectations make the company unsure of its ability to
maintain the dividend at current levels'. He added that while IBM would try
to achieve job cuts voluntarily, if business conditions did not improve
significantly 'it is likely that some business units will be unable to
maintain full employment in 1993'.
Since 1986 the company has cut its workforce by about 100,000 to some
300,000. Nearly half the job cuts announced yesterday will be in Europe but
full details were unclear last night.
IBM Germany, however, said that next year it would cut rather more than the
2,000 jobs it shed in 1993. It would not rule out further redundancies as a
way of reducing the workforce.
IBM UK said it expected to cut up to 1,000 jobs in 1993, the same as this
year. By the end of 1993, the workforce could be down to 13,000 in the UK,
about 5,000 less than in 1990.
Worldwide, the company is to cut its development spending by about Dollars
1bn, or roughly one sixth, in 1993, reduce capital spending and cut sales,
general and administrative expenses by Dollars 1bn.
IBM added that its fourth-quarter operating results were only likely to be
around break-even - well below Wall Street forecasts - because of the
unexpected depth of the business downturn, particularly in Europe, prolonged
worldwide economic weakness and market pressures to cut hardware prices.
It warned that it expected the unfavourable conditions to continue into
1993.
This is the latest in a series of restructurings by IBM since the late 1980s
as it has struggled with the global economic slowdown, which began in the
US, and the extremely rapid pace of change in the computer industry.
IBM, which has dominated the market for large, mainframe computers, has
suffered from the shift of demand to smaller, desk-top models because its
bureaucratic structure has not responded sufficiently quickly.
The latest round of cuts comes on top of Dollars 5.4bn of special pre-tax
charges so far this year to cover plant closures and 40,000 job cuts. The
total charge this year comes to Dollars 11.4bn.
Mr Akers said trading conditions had deteriorated more precipitously than
expected. The company said its personal computer business, which introduced
an inexpensive new line in the autumn, was seeing strong sales growth and
was moving towards profitability in 1993, but the mainframe business had
suffered a 10 per cent fall in revenues during 1992.
Asked by journalists whether he had considered stepping down, Mr Akers, who
has been chairman for six years, said he had given no thought to the matter
because IBM was on the right track and the board supported him.
Big Blue turns mean and lean to survive recession, Page 23
Debt rating for review, Page 29
World stocks, Page 37
</TEXT>
