<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / Fresh disarray in US-Mexico narcotics case: Doctor kidnapped
to face trial over murdered agent is cleared by judge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP and DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOS ANGELES, MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MEXICAN doctor kidnapped and taken across the border to the US to stand
trial over a drug agent's murder was found innocent by a judge in Los
Angeles yesterday, AP reports from Los Angeles.
The decision came as a stunning blow to the prosecution in the case, which
has caused political controversy in both Mexico and the US.
The judge ruled that the US government never had sufficient evidence to try
Dr Humberto Alavarez Machain in connection with the death in 1985 of the US
drugs agent Enrique Camarena.
'There has to be stronger evidence than you have offered to find that a man
is guilty of kidnapping, murder and torture,' District Judge Edward Rafeedie
told the prosecutors. 'This does not rise to the level required to get this
case to the jury.'
He accused federal prosecutors of presenting 'the wildest speculation'.
The prosecutors had argued that when Mr Camarena was kidnapped and tortured
to death by Mexico's drug lords, they had Dr Alvarez Machain inject him with
drugs to keep him alive for further torture.
The doctor was kidnapped by bounty hunters in Guadalajara in April 1990 and
was then spirited to the US for trial.
The US Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) maintains that his kidnapping
was legal and justified.
But the Mexican government protested that the doctor's kidnapping violated
Mexican sovereignty and it has repeatedly demanded his return.
In the latest trial - the third resulting from the drug agent's killing -
the defence attorney said there were no puncture marks or drug residue in
the agent's body to prove he had been given injections. Nor were there
fingerprints to link a syringe found at the torture house to Dr Alvarez
Machain, he said.
Seven people have been convicted in US courts in the Camarena killing and
more than two dozen in Mexico.
Judge Rafeedie had already refused to grant a judgment of acquittal for Dr
Alvarez Machain's co-defendant, Ruben Zuno Arce, a brother-in-law of former
Mexican President Luis Echeverria.
He also ruled earlier that the doctor's kidnapping violated US-Mexico
extradition treaties and that US courts did not have jurisdiction to try
him. But on that ruling, the judge eventually was overturned by the US
Supreme Court.
Damian Fraser adds from Mexico City: Allegations highlighted lately in the
case of the murdered drugs agent have come at an inconvenient time for the
Mexican government, which is anxious to build ties to the incoming Clinton
administration in the US.
According to two witnesses called by the US government, high Mexican
officials were all in the pay of the Guadalajara drug cartel.
The witnesses claimed that these officials were present at meetings in which
Mr Camarena's murder was planned and visited the house where Mr Camarena was
held on the day he was killed.
In the view of the Mexican government the charges are 'based on the
testimony of delinquents and criminals who do not merit credibility in light
of their personal history'.
The accusations, whether true or not, are likely to draw attention to the
greatest flaw in the Mexican state: corruption in the legal and political
system.
In practically all the big drug scandals over the past decade, be it the
murder of Mr Camarena, the prison riot between rival drug gangs at Matamoros
last year, or the shoot-out between the army and police in Veracruz this
year, officials of the police, the army or the government have been
implicated in narcotics trafficking.
The police are also largely responsible for Mexico's dismal human rights
record, another issue likely to be raised by the US Congress when it
considers the proposed North American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
