<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Shake-out forecast in pulp and paper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPE'S paper and pulp industry faces accelerating rationalisation,
according to Mr Bo Berggren, chief executive of Stora, the region's largest
paper group.
Mr Berggren, speaking at the FT world pulp and paper conference in London,
pointed out the industry remained far too fragmented. Many plants,
particularly in France, Italy and Spain, were outdated and small. In these
countries there were uncoated woodfree paper machines still running which
dated from before the war.
Mr Dick Eykel, board member at KNP, the Dutch group, blamed overcapacity for
the industry's woes. Prices were at the lowest real levels for the last few
decades.
'It's a shame when some markets are growing at 9.5 per cent that an industry
is capable of ruining itself through overcapacity. It's a question of bad
management,' said Mr Eykel. He called for companies to time investments
better.
The industry's restructuring should ultimately lead to a more stable
environment and growth patterns which were less cyclical, said Mr Alain
Soulas, chief executive of Arjo Wiggins Appleton, the Franco-British group.
The consolidation should help reduce the degree of over-investment by
combining expansion plans. The far more consolidated US industry had
achieved an average return over the last 15 years of 12 per cent compared
with the European industry's 8 per cent.
</TEXT>
