FT  15 DEC 92 / Spending curbs on BBC criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN TUSA, outgoing managing director of the BBC World Service, attacked
the government yesterday for planning to cut the organisation's budget by
Pounds 5m a year from 1994.
The prospect of a reduced budget comes as the World Service, which has a
regular audience of 120m worldwide, celebrates its 60th anniversary. Last
week Prince Charles argued that the BBC World Service should continue to
expand services.
Mr Tusa said his argument was not with the Foreign Office, which funds the
World Service through grants, but the Treasury, which was threatening the
cut.
Mr Tusa said: 'If this cut goes ahead, it will go straight to programmes. It
will be very, very damaging.'
A Pounds 5m-a-year reduction from next year's Pounds 172m budget would mean
the loss of about seven hours of foreign-language broadcasting a week.
The BBC opens negotiations with the Foreign Office next year for its next
three-year funding period, which runs from April 1994.
Mr Tusa said: 'It seems to me we cannot start with the assumption that,
whatever happens in the negotiations, we get Pounds 5m less.'
He also argued that there should be more practical co-operation between the
government-funded World Service radio and World Service Television, which is
funded through the commercial arm of the BBC.
