<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / Brick mountain walls in builders: Andrew Taylor finds
serious overcapacity among construction materials producers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH construction industry, already reeling from the worst recession
for more than half a century, is bracing itself for another round of company
failures, plant closures and job losses.
Overcapacity among contractors and building material producers is such that
further cuts are inevitable, even if the recession were to end tomorrow.
As it is, most forecasters expect construction demand to fall further next
year - by between 1 per cent and 2 per cent - in spite of measures to
encourage greater expenditure on building announced in the government Autumn
Statement.
Redundancies will consequently continue to rise in an industry that has
already lost more than 400,000 jobs since summer 1989.
According to Mr Howard Seymour, construction analyst for stockbrokers
Barclays de Zoete Wedd: 'Even if construction demand were to stabilise at
levels prevailing in 1986, which was a reasonably good year for output and
sales, there would still be substantial overcapacity.'
At the heart of the industry's troubles is the massive investment in new
capacity made by companies in the late 1980s to meet booming demand for new
buildings.
Brick manufacturers are estimated to have spent more than Pounds 200m on new
plant during the period, only to find that demand for their products shrank
as housing and commercial property markets went into recession.
Brick producers increased production capacity from 4.5bn bricks a year to
5bn between 1987 and 1989. Closures and mothballing of kilns have now
reduced capacity to 3.7bn. Even so, sales of bricks this year will be less
than 3bn, or 19 per cent less than kilns are capable of producing.
The effect of such overcapacity has been a savage reduction in prices
charged by building material producers and contractors. Mr Robert Napier,
managing director of Redland, one of the country's biggest building
materials producers, estimates that prices of concrete, bricks and tiles
have fallen by between 10 per cent and 15 per cent in the past 12 months.
'It is madness,' Mr Napier says. 'In south-east England we are virtually
giving away valuable finite reserves of sand and gravel, at very little
profit.
'The only way that prices can recover is if inefficient plants and producers
are removed from the market, preferably through mergers and subsequent
rationalisation.'
That may be difficult to achieve in markets where there are many very small
family-owned companies. They have no other business interests to fall back
on, and therefore seek to increase volume when profits fall, thus putting
even greater strain on prices.
The only solution for larger companies may be to buy out small businesses or
wait for them to fail.
Meanwhile, annual sales of ready-mixed concrete, one of the most basic of
building materials, have declined by almost a third since 1989 from 29.6m cu
metres to 20m. Manufacturing capacity has been reduced by only about 2m cu
metres during the period.
The overheads of running a concrete-mixing plant, with its much lower use of
energy, are small by comparison with a brick or cement works. The incentive
to close a plant, which might mean losing an entire local market, is
therefore much less.
Profits on ready-mixed concrete have fallen to about Pounds 1 a tonne
compared with Pounds 4 to Pounds 5 a tonne three years ago. Mr Napier says
producers that lack their own supply of aggregates can only be selling at a
loss.
Road construction is one of the few areas of building and civil engineering
to have withstood the recession. Sales of coated stone are holding at about
37 1/2 m tonnes a year. Unfortunately, blacktop manufacturing capacity has
risen even faster than sales. In the Thames Valley alone there is estimated
surplus capacity of at least 5m tonnes a year. Prices have plummeted, and
most blacktop producers will be making a loss on sales, according to the
industry.
Steel producers have also suffered as construction demand has dwindled. More
than 100 steel fabricators have ceased trading or gone into receivership
since 1989, according to the British Constructional Steelwork Association.
Numbers employed by the industry have fallen from 60,000 to 40,000.
In spite of those reductions, capacity continues to outstrip demand. Almost
90,000 tonnes of construction steel is estimated to have been sold this
year, compared with a potential manufacturing capacity of about 1.1m tonnes.
The arithmetic is inescapable: building material producers must continue
working on short time, or introduce extended closures over Christmas (as
seems increasingly likely), or plants will have to be mothballed or closed
permanently.
Contractors face similar overcapacity. Competition for work is intense. Many
contractors are winning work at a loss or bidding for work at prices that
only just cover their overheads, according to Sir Brian Hill, president of
the Building Employers Confederation, the industry's biggest trade
association.
The overriding need is to generate cash from progress payments to meet
monthly bills and pay off borrowings, Sir Brian says. 'The construction
industry faces a long haul before output reaches a level where the rise in
unemployment will first be checked, and then reversed.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
