FT  15 DEC 92 / Financial Reporting Council willing to adopt audit board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FINANCIAL Reporting Council would be willing to consider taking
responsibility for auditing as well as accounting standards, its chairman
said yesterday.
Sir Ron Dearing said he would consider bringing the Auditing Practices Board
under the council's umbrella if the accountancy profession so wished.
Pressure has been growing for removal of the board from ownership of the
Consultative Committee of Accountancy Bodies, the consortium of the six
leading accountancy professional bodies.
The council already controls the Accounting Standards Board and urgent
issues task force, which set new standards, and the Financial Reporting
Review Panel, which polices them.
The council was established to replace and enhance work on improving
financial reporting led by the Accounting Standards Committee, which was
controlled by the accountancy profession.
Sir Ron emphasised that the council was a new body that could not sustain
many new responsibilities over the next year. But he said: 'I am not making
a pitch, but in the longer term, if it was the wish of others, we would
provide a constructive response.'
Mr Bill Morrison, APB chairman, said recently he was willing to consider the
board becoming independent of the profession, but stressed that it had many
non-professional members and was not impeded by its existing ownership.
Mr John Roques, senior partner of Touche Ross, recently said that public
confidence in accounting could be restored only by removing audit
standard-setting and regulation and the development of ethical codes from
the profession.
Ernst &amp; Young has also called for a change in the regulatory regime.
</TEXT>
