<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / Coal gets boost from Eastern Electricity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EASTERN Electricity gave coal a boost yesterday by becoming the first
regional electricity distributor to sign up a new deal for coal-based power.
But other companies seemed hesitant to follow suit.
Eastern, the largest of the regional distributors in England and Wales,
signed a five-year agreement with PowerGen, one of the two leading
generators, to take 21 terawatt (billion kilowatt) hours of electricity. The
deal, worth more than Pounds 100m a year, equates to 8m tonnes of coal.
The contract takes effect from March 31 when all British Coal's current coal
contracts are due to expire. The energy review by Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade secretary, has thrown negotiations into uncertainty.
Dr James Smith, Eastern's chairman and chief executive, said the deal was
flexible enough to cope with changes in energy or regulatory policy.
He added: 'We also believe that it does not prejudice the outcome of the
current energy review but in fact helps break the deadlock in electricity
contracts and is a positive move towards securing the future of coal.'
Dr Smith preferred the certainty of a five-year deal to the one-year deals
which both Mr Heseltine and Prof Stephen Littlechild, the electricity
regulator, have indicated might be more appropriate until the review is
complete.
The deal would meet about 17 per cent of Eastern's needs over the period. Dr
Smith hoped to sign a similar deal with National Power, the other large
generator, by Christmas.
Mr Ed Wallis, chief executive of PowerGen, said he expected to complete
deals with other regional elewctricity companies. Although he doubted
whether they would be done by Christmas.
Neither company was prepared to discuss the deal in detail, but it is
understood to be based on the price of 3.26p a unit, which has been on offer
since the coal negotiations started several months ago.
The deal excludes Eastern from paying 'uplift' - the variable charge added
to bulk electricity to finance the running of the electricity system.
Mr Neil Clarke, chairman of British Coal, said the deal would bring
much-needed stability to the coal market. He hoped other regional companies
would sign five-year deals to give British Coal the breathing space it
needed to make its operations more efficient.
Other regional companies gave a mixed response. One said it would sign
nothing until the review was completed, although another indicated that it
might be ready to sign by mid January.
Mr Jim Keohane, power purchasing manager of East Midlands, said his company
was keen to see a five-year deal, although none was imminent. It was working
with other regional companies and was in active discussions with the
generators.
</TEXT>
