<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / W Midlands manufacturers' orders continue to fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADING conditions for West Midlands engineering companies, whose experience
acts as a barometer for the UK manufacturing sector, continued to
deteriorate in the three months to November, with a growing proportion of
companies reporting a decline in domestic and export orders.
The quarterly business survey of the Engineering Employers' Federation West
Midlands, covering 475 companies, showed that the percentage of companies
reporting lower domestic orders rose to 51 in November from 36 in August.
Those reporting lower export orders rose to 31 per cent from 26 per cent.
The Autumn Statement and its associated interest rate cut came too late in
the November quarter to affect the immediate commercial prospects of
companies covered in the survey. Mr David Botterill, chief executive of the
EEF West Midlands, noted that 'the next two quarters will provide critical
evidence of the future direction of the UK economy'.
But the shift in the government's economic policy failed to ignite
commercial confidence. The proportion of companies cutting capital
investment was 24 per cent, scarcely changed from August.
Nearly half of the engineering companies reported that utilisation of
capacity and profits were both lower at the end of November, compared with
33 per cent at the end of August. Companies expecting capacity utilisation
to decline in the next three months rose to 28 per cent from 21 per cent
three months ago.
That points to a further reduction in jobs and 32 per cent of companies are
expecting a cut in the number of their employees over the next three months.
Only 10 per cent of companies intend to take on more people, the lowest
proportion recorded this year by the federation.
</TEXT>
