FT  15 DEC 92 / Teletext games to stimulate audience
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TECHNIQUES used to raise newspaper circulation, including cash prize games,
will be applied to stimulate interest in teletext from the beginning of next
year.
The first signs of a shake-up in the teletext service on ITV and Channel 4
will come just after midnight on January 1 when Teletext, a company in which
Associated Newspapers has a 45 per cent stake, takes over from Oracle.
Earlier this year Associated, with partners Philips Electronics and Media
Ventures, won the teletext franchise with a bid of Pounds 8.2m a year
compared with Oracle's Pounds 6.6m in one of the more obscure tenders for
commercial broadcasting licences.
They have since bought the right to use the generic name teletext as the
name of the service.
More than 10m homes have television sets that can receive teletext - the
text information service - but only a third of them regularly use it.
Papers such as the Daily Mail will carry game cards which will also be
available at newsagents. Results of games with prizes of up to Pounds 1,000
a day will be broadcast on Teletext. There will be free games for children
and others played using premium rate telephone calls.
Sir David English, chairman of Teletext, said: 'We think we can do better
than Oracle. We don't think they were very imaginative in either their
marketing or their journalism.'
It plans to change the balance of its service throughout each 24-hour
period, with pages devoted to mothers and children during the afternoon,
family entertainment during the evening and more adult- oriented pages late
at night.
For the first time, there will be a separate news service for each of the 14
ITV regions.
The basic news service from the Press Association will be supplemented by
journalists from the Mail group, owned by Associated Newspapers, and local
correspondents.
Sir David said teletext advertisers had signed up at rates 25 per cent to 30
per cent higher than that achieved by Oracle.
</TEXT>
