FT  15 DEC 92 / Lamont optimistic about recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont, the chancellor, has expressed optimism that next year
would be one of progress for the economy. But yesterday he faced a call for
a more balanced economic policy over the medium term and further supply-side
measures to increase Britain's growth potential, Emma Tucker and Ralph
Atkins write.
Mr Lamont writes in The House Magazine, the Commons publication, that the
scene is set for recovery and growth. The right environment is in place for
a restoration of confidence.
He admits that recovery has failed to take root so far, but adds: 'In
Britain we face a growing threat to activity from the slowdown in the world
economy. At the same time, the risks from inflation are diminishing. That is
why the balance of macroeconomic policy overall has been tilted to give more
weight to growth.'
However, in its latest journal, the Society of Business Economists
criticises economic management in the 1980s for relying on single policy
measures rather than on a balanced and consistent economic package.
Although the decade saw some supply-side improvements in the economy, other
difficulties were ignored, including the weakening of the manufacturing base
and the tendency to use too many resources for consumption rather than
investment, it says.
Mr Richard Freeman, chief economist at ICI, writes: 'The UK needs a
strategic vision which is capable of changing attitudes throughout society
about the economy's performance and particularly attitudes to manufacturing
industry. . . It has to include a realistic commitment to Europe and certain
institutional changes.'
Sir Peter Walters, the chairman of Midland Bank, today becomes the first of
the clearing bank chairmen to meet Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to
discuss the government's review of banks' interest rate policy.
The Business Economist. Society of Business Economists, 11 Bay Tree Walk,
Watford, Herts WD1 3RX. Pounds 11
</TEXT>
