FT  15 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Anti-cartel penalties tightened by Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Japanese government has toughened the criminal penalties for the
formation of cartels, following pressure from the US and recommendations
from the Fair Trade Commission, the country's anti-monopoly body.
Meanwhile, a separate advisory panel to the Ministry of International Trade
and Industry (Miti) yesterday recommended that the government increase
protection for intellectual property rights by toughening fines and
redefining products eligible for protection.
Japanese anti-monopoly legislation had made no distinction between a cartel
violation by an individual and a company, and had kept fines for the two at
the same level. But an amendment to the legislation provides for a
distinction and for far tougher penalties on companies.
Under the new legislation, Japanese companies violating the criminal
provisions of the law will be subject to a maximum fine of Y100m (Pounds
526,000), up from Y5m.
The changes follow demands made by the US government at the bilateral
Structural Impediments Initiative (SII) talks.
</TEXT>
