<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / US marines prepare first deep land penetration in Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOGADISHU, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Marines and army troops were preparing last night to make their first
deep land penetration of the starvation-ridden interior of Somalia, writes
Julian Ozanne in Mogadishu.
According to US military officials, marines will start a 24-hour operation
this morning to take control of Baidoa, the 'City of Death' at the centre of
Somalia's hunger zone where up to 100 people are dying each day in that town
alone.
US officials said troops would today begin moving out of Mogadishu in a
70-vehicle armoured convoy and a score of helicopters along the
bandit-plagued dirt road to Baidoa, roughly 150 miles north-west of the
capital.
By evening the road should be secured by 'Humvee' armoured cars and
Cobra-helicopter flying patrols. Special forces commandos would move into
positions around Baidoa by nightfall to prepare for an advance on the town
at dawn tomorrow. In total 600 to 700 troops, including a small contingent
of French soldiers, would be used.
In Mogadishu confusion was still apparent among US forces about their exact
role in disarming bandits, freelance gunmen and rival clan-militias. Col
Fred Peck, the marines' spokesman, said he had received no orders to disarm
Somalis and described the policy on disarmament as a 'very ambiguous
situation'.
He was speaking after Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary general,
said at the weekend President George Bush had discreetly promised to disarm
the warring factions.
Michael Littlejohns adds from New York: Mr Boutros Ghali played down any
policy difference with the Americans at a news conference in New York. Given
that the UN must also be consulted before coalition troops could withdraw,
he would try to ensure there was adequate security in Somalia to enable the
world body then to begin a new peacekeeping operation and efforts at
national reconciliation.
</TEXT>
