<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 92 / International Company News: Maho in collaboration talks with
rival Deckel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE DISCLOSURE yesterday that Maho, the stricken German machine tool group,
is in collaboration talks with rival Deckel has highlighted the urgency of
the industry's search for cost-savings.
Mr Bodo Viets, Maho chairman since the end of June, said he could give no
further details for fear of derailing the negotiations. He was speaking
after winning shareholder approval for a capital restructuring which forms
the launch-pad for his recovery plans.
He told the annual meeting in Munich that group losses in the current
financial year would fall to less than DM100m (Dollars 66.6m), against the
DM157m reported in the 12 months to end-June, 1992. The deficit at Maho AG,
the German parent, reached DM22m at the half-way mark, he said.
Sales, which slumped 31 per cent last year to DM442m, will fall a further 10
per cent in the current year, he added.
The company, which aims to return to profit in 1993/94, is expected to fall
under the effective control of a group of eight banks, including Deutsche
Bank, Bayerische Vereinsbank and Commmerzbank, after the annual meeting
approved a complex package which should reduce the holding of the Babel
family from around 54 per cent to 25 per cent.
Last week Maho and Traub, a machine tools group which lost DM30m in 1991 and
had a first-half DM16m deficit this year, announced the merger of their
distribution networks. The companies estimated the deal would save each
group DM8.5m in 1993 and twice that in the following year.
Talks are to continue on co-operation in purchasing, manufacture and
research and development, but full merger or share swaps are not on the
agenda.
The alliance followed the establishment of a similar collaboration,
effective from January, between Gildemeister, which lost DM29m in 1991 and
Deckel which expects a DM70m deficit in the current year.
The machine tool industry has been especially hard hit by the investment
cuts which have characterised international industry's reaction to
recession. With the domestic downturn accelerating - new orders at Deckel
were down 6 per cent at the end of September - the need to rationalise is
growing more urgent.
After two years of retrenchment, the scope for job cuts is limited and
savings have to be found elsewhere. Maho, which in the past year reduced its
workforce by a third to 2,320, has introduced widespread short-time and
plans a further reduction of 400 places during the current year.
So far, alliances have been forged between companies which do not compete
directly with one another. While Maho is a milling specialist, Traub's main
strength is in computer-steered turning centres. Gildemeister makes turning
machines, while Deckel concentrates on milling.
Mr Viets, who said talks were under way with other companies, noted a merger
with Deckel would have grave consequences because plants would have to be
shut.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
