<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How do we dare treat young doctors as we do, expecting them to take life and
death decisions while working 80 hours a week? Most of us must surely come
into contact with hospitals from time to time, and thus know what is going
on, in a way that is not merely theoretical. Yet nothing changes. The last
episode in BBC2's remarkable documentary series Doctors To Be (7.50) shows
how disillusion and bitterness have replaced excitement and idealism in the
eight years since the 10 young doctors began their training. Also coming to
an end tonight is 'Allo 'Allo, that extraordinary repository of English
prejudices. Italians are amorous cowards, Germans are ludicrous prigs, the
French can speak English only with the most absurd accent, and the English
as represented by the officer class are brainless. Repeats will run for the
rest of our lives (8.00 BBC1). Witchcraft (9.00 BBC2) described as a period
thriller, is yet another modern fiction straddling the centuries. Witches,
witchfinders, and adultery are the chief ingredients, and the stars, in a
Cotswold setting, are Peter McEnery, Lisa Harrow and Alan Howard.
</TEXT>
